    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "targeted_sweep10_econ_threshold_2016",
    "description": "Economic threshold sweep in the 2016-block retarget regime. Maps which economic_split levels produce a decisive v27 win once sufficient run time is given for the first difficulty retarget to fire.\nSweep9 confirmed that at econ=0.70, the cascade completes at t\u22488,106s when the first v27 difficulty retarget fires (~50% drop). Committed v26 pool losses jumped from ~9% (pre-retarget) to ~56% (post-retarget), far exceeding the 13.3% tolerance. The open question is: does the cascade complete at lower economic levels (econ=0.35\u20130.60)?\nThe key mechanism:\n  - Pre-retarget: committed v26 pools lose only ~1\u20139% (below 13.3% tolerance)\n  - Post-retarget: difficulty drops ~50% \u2192 profitability spike \u2192 loss spikes sharply\n  - Whether committed pools are forced to switch depends on how large the post-retarget\n    loss is, which is modulated by the price gap (i.e., economic_split)\n  - At econ=0.70, loss=56% >> tolerance; at lower econ the price gap is smaller \u2192\n    loss spike may be smaller \u2192 may stay below tolerance\n\nExpected hypotheses:\n  - econ=0.82: v27 wins via price signal alone (same as sweep8, no change)\n  - econ=0.70: v27 wins post-retarget (confirmed by sweep9)\n  - econ=0.60: uncertain \u2014 price gap is narrower; post-retarget loss may not exceed tolerance\n  - econ=0.50: likely stuck contested even post-retarget \u2014 price gap too small\n  - econ=0.35: stuck contested \u2014 economic minority cannot trigger forced switches\n\nThis determines the 2016-block economic threshold: the minimum economic_split at which the difficulty adjustment cascade completes. This is the realistic Bitcoin fork resolution condition (2-week retarget window).\nIMPORTANT: Run with --retarget-interval 2016 and --duration 12000 (t=8106s retarget + ~4000s post-retarget dynamics = 12,106s sufficient) Use 13000s to ensure margin regardless of timing variance.\n",
